# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arduino
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The **Arduino Uno** is a series of open-source microcontroller board based on a diverse range of microcontrollers (MCU).
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] It was initially developed and released by the Arduino company in 2010.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The microcontroller board is equipped with sets of digital and analog input/output (I/O) pins that may be interfaced to various expansion boards (shields) and other circuits.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The board has 14 digital I/O pins (six capable of PWM output), 6 analog I/O pins, and is programmable with the Arduino IDE (Integrated Development Environment), via a type B USB cable.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] It can be powered by a USB cable or a barrel connector that accepts voltages between 7 and 20 volts, such as a rectangular 9-volt battery.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] It has the same microcontroller as the Arduino Nano board, and the same headers as the Leonardo board.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The hardware reference design is distributed under a Creative Commons Attribution Share-Alike 2.5 license and is available on the Arduino website.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Layout and production files for some versions of the hardware are also available.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The word "uno" means "one" in Italian and was chosen to mark a major redesign of the Arduino hardware and software.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The Uno board was the successor of the Duemilanove release and was the 9th version in a series of USB-based Arduino boards.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Version 1.0 of the Arduino IDE for the Arduino Uno board has now evolved to newer releases.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The ATmega328 on the board comes preprogrammed with a bootloader that allows uploading new code to it without the use of an external hardware programmer.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] While the Uno communicates using the original STK500 protocol, it differs from all preceding boards in that it does not use a FTDI USB-to-UART serial chip.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Instead, it uses the Atmega16U2 (Atmega8U2 up to version R2) programmed as a USB-to-serial converter.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The Arduino project started at the Interaction Design Institute Ivrea (IDII) in Ivrea, Italy.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] At that time, the students used a BASIC Stamp microcontroller, at a considerable price.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] In 2003, Hernando Barragán created the development platform *Wiring* as a Master's thesis project at IDII, under the supervision of Massimo Banzi and Casey Reas, who are known for work on the Processing language.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The project goal was to create simple, low-cost tools for creating digital projects by non-engineers.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The Wiring platform consisted of a printed circuit board (PCB) with an ATmega168 microcontroller, an IDE based on Processing, and library functions to easily program the microcontroller.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] In 2003, Massimo Banzi, with David Mellis, another IDII student, and David Cuartielles, added support for the cheaper ATmega8 microcontroller to Wiring.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] But instead of continuing the work on Wiring, they forked the project and renamed it *Arduino*.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Early Arduino boards used the FTDI USB-to-UART serial chip and an ATmega168.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The Uno differed from all preceding boards by featuring the ATmega328P microcontroller and an ATmega16U2 (Atmega8U2 up to version R2) programmed as a USB-to-serial converter.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] In June 2023, Arduino released two new flavors of the Uno; R4 Minima and R4 Wifi.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] These mark a departure from previous boards as they use Renesas RA4M1 ARM Cortex M4 microcontroller, and the R4 Wifi a Espressif ESP32-S3-MINI co-processor.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] These versions are form factor, pin and power compatible with version R1 to R3, so should be largely be able to be drop in replacements.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] In October 2025, Arduino released the Arduino UNO Q, a board with Linux support and WIFi, featuring a Qualcomm co-processor following their acquisition by Qualcomm.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] It also has a LED matrix and Bluetooth support.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Two Uno R4 boards are available: Uno R4 Minima and Uno R4 WiFi.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The latter has a WiFi coprocessor and LED matrix, but the Minima doesn't.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The Arduino Uno Q has a dual processor setup with the Qualcomm Dragonwing serving as the MPU (microprocessor) and the ARM based STM32U585 as the MCU (microcontroller).
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Unlike the others, the UNO Q is capable of running Linux while also introducing Arduino App Lab.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Each of the 14 digital pins and 6 analog pins on the Uno can be used as an input or output, under software control (using pinMode(), digitalWrite(), and digitalRead() functions).
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Each pin can provide or receive 20 mA as the recommended operating condition and has an internal pull-up resistor (disconnected by default) of 20-50K ohm.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] A maximum of 40mA must not be exceeded on any I/O pin to avoid permanent damage to the microcontroller.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The Uno has 6 analog inputs, labeled A0 through A5; each provides 10 bits of resolution (i.e.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] By default, they measure from ground to 5 volts, though it is possible to change the upper end of the range using the AREF pin and the analogReference() function.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The Arduino/Genuino Uno has a number of facilities for communicating with a computer, another Arduino/Genuino board, or other microcontrollers.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The ATmega328 provides UART TTL (5V) serial communication, which is available on digital pins 0 (RX) and 1 (TX).
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] An ATmega16U2 on the board channels this serial communication over USB and appears as a virtual com port to software on the computer.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The 16U2 firmware uses the standard USB COM drivers, and no external driver is needed.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] However, on Windows, a .inf file is required.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Arduino Software (IDE) includes a serial monitor which allows simple textual data to be sent to and from the board.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The RX and TX LEDs on the board will flash when data is being transmitted via the USB-to-serial chip and USB connection to the computer (but not for serial communication on pins 0 and 1).
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] A SoftwareSerial library allows serial communication on any of the Uno's digital pins.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Rather than requiring a physical press of the reset button before an upload, the Arduino/Genuino Uno board is designed in a way that allows it to be reset by the software running on a connected computer.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] One of the hardware flow control lines (DTR) of the ATmega8U2/16U2 is connected to the reset line of the ATmega328 via a 100 nanofarad capacitor.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] When this line is asserted (taken low), the reset line drops long enough to reset the chip.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] When the Uno is connected to a computer running Mac OS X or Linux, it resets each time a connection is made to it from software (via USB).
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] For the following half-second or so, the bootloader is running on the Uno.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] While it is programmed to ignore malformed data (i.e. anything besides an upload of new code), it will intercept the first few bytes of data sent to the board after a connection is opened.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The following table compares official Arduino boards, and has a similar layout as a table in the Arduino Nano article.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] The table is split with a dark bar into two high-level microcontroller groups: 8-bit AVR cores (upper group), and 32-bit ARM Cortex-M cores (lower group).
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] Though 3rd-party boards have similar board names it doesn't automatically mean they are 100% identical to official Arduino boards.
[src:arduino/arduino-uno] 3rd-party boards often have a different voltage regulator / different USB-to-UART chip / different color solder mask, and some have a different USB connector or additional features, too.
[src:arduino/arduino] Arduino board designs use a variety of microprocessors and controllers.
[src:arduino/arduino] The boards are equipped with sets of digital and analog input/output (I/O) pins that may be interfaced to various expansion boards ('shields') or breadboards (for prototyping) and other circuits.
[src:arduino/arduino] The boards feature serial communications interfaces, including Universal Serial Bus (USB) on some models, which are also used for loading programs.
[src:arduino/arduino] The microcontrollers can be programmed using the C and C++ programming languages (Embedded C), using a standard API which is also known as the **Arduino Programming Language**, inspired by the Processing language and used with a modified version of the Processing IDE.
[src:arduino/arduino] In addition to using traditional compiler toolchains, the Arduino project provides an integrated development environment (IDE) and a command line tool developed in Go.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino project began in 2005 as a tool for students at the Interaction Design Institute Ivrea, Italy, aiming to provide a low-cost and easy way for novices and professionals to create devices that interact with their environment using sensors and actuators.
[src:arduino/arduino] Common examples of such devices intended for makers include simple robots, thermostats, and motion detectors.
[src:arduino/arduino] The name *Arduino* comes from the Bar di Re Arduino, where some of the project's founders used to meet.
[src:arduino/arduino] This bar is in Ivrea, Italy and was named after Arduin.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino project was started at the Interaction Design Institute Ivrea (IDII) in Ivrea, Italy.
[src:arduino/arduino] At that time, the students used a BASIC Stamp microcontroller at a cost of $50.
[src:arduino/arduino] In 2004, Hernando Barragán created the development platform *Wiring* as a Master's thesis project at IDII, under the supervision of Massimo Banzi and Casey Reas.
[src:arduino/arduino] Casey Reas is known for co-creating, with Ben Fry, the Processing development platform.
[src:arduino/arduino] The project goal was to create simple, low cost tools for creating digital projects by non-engineers.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Wiring platform consisted of a printed circuit board (PCB) with an ATmega128 microcontroller, an IDE based on Processing and library functions to easily program the microcontroller.
[src:arduino/arduino] In 2005, Massimo Banzi, with David Mellis, another IDII student, and David Cuartielles, extended Wiring by adding support for the cheaper ATmega8 microcontroller.
[src:arduino/arduino] The new project, forked from Wiring, was called *Arduino*.
[src:arduino/arduino] The initial Arduino core team consisted of Massimo Banzi, David Cuartielles, Tom Igoe, Gianluca Martino, and David Mellis.
[src:arduino/arduino] Following the completion of the platform, lighter and less expensive versions were distributed in the open-source community.
[src:arduino/arduino] It was estimated in mid-2011 that over 300,000 official Arduinos had been commercially produced, and in 2013 that 700,000 official boards were in users' hands.
[src:arduino/arduino] In early 2008, the five co-founders of the Arduino project created a company, Arduino LLC, to hold the trademarks associated with Arduino.
[src:arduino/arduino] The manufacture and sale of the boards were to be done by external companies, and Arduino LLC would get a royalty from them.
[src:arduino/arduino] The founding bylaws of Arduino LLC specified that each of the five founders transfer ownership of the Arduino brand to the newly formed company.
[src:arduino/arduino] At the end of 2008, Gianluca Martino's company, Smart Projects, registered the Arduino trademark in Italy and kept this a secret from the other co-founders for about two years.
[src:arduino/arduino] This was revealed when the Arduino company tried to register the trademark in other areas of the world (they originally registered only in the US), and discovered that it was already registered in Italy.
[src:arduino/arduino] Negotiations with Martino and his firm to bring the trademark under the control of the original Arduino company failed.
[src:arduino/arduino] In 2014, Smart Projects began refusing to pay royalties.
[src:arduino/arduino] They then appointed a new CEO, Federico Musto, who renamed the company *Arduino SRL* and created the website *arduino.org*, copying the graphics and layout of the original *arduino.cc*.
[src:arduino/arduino] This resulted in a rift in the Arduino development team.
[src:arduino/arduino] In January 2015, Arduino LLC filed a lawsuit against Arduino SRL.
[src:arduino/arduino] In May 2015, Arduino LLC created the worldwide trademark **Genuino**, used as brand name outside the United States.
[src:arduino/arduino] At the World Maker Faire in New York on 1 October 2016, Arduino LLC co-founder and CEO Massimo Banzi and Arduino SRL CEO Federico Musto announced the merger of the two companies, forming Arduino AG.
[src:arduino/arduino] Around that same time, Massimo Banzi announced that in addition to the company a new Arduino Foundation would be launched as "a new beginning for Arduino", but this decision was withdrawn later.
[src:arduino/arduino] In April 2017, Wired reported that Musto had "fabricated his academic record...
[src:arduino/arduino] On his company's website, personal LinkedIn accounts, and even on Italian business documents, Musto was, until recently, listed as holding a Ph.D. from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:arduino/arduino] In some cases, his biography also claimed an MBA from New York University." Wired reported that neither university had any record of Musto's attendance, and Musto later admitted in an interview with Wired that he had never earned those degrees.
[src:arduino/arduino] The controversy surrounding Musto continued when, in July 2017, he reportedly pulled many open source licenses, schematics, and code from the Arduino website, prompting scrutiny and outcry.
[src:arduino/arduino] By 2017 Arduino 'AG' owned many Arduino trademarks.
[src:arduino/arduino] In July 2017 BCMI, founded by Massimo Banzi, David Cuartielles, David Mellis and Tom Igoe, acquired Arduino AG and all the Arduino trademarks.
[src:arduino/arduino] Fabio Violante is the new CEO replacing Federico Musto, who no longer works for Arduino AG.
[src:arduino/arduino] In October 2017, Arduino announced its partnership with Arm Holdings (ARM).
[src:arduino/arduino] The announcement said, in part, "ARM recognized independence as a core value of Arduino ... without any lock-in with the ARM architecture".
[src:arduino/arduino] Arduino intends to continue to work with all technology vendors and architectures.
[src:arduino/arduino] Under Violante's guidance, the company started growing again and releasing new designs.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Genuino trademark was dismissed and all products were branded again with the Arduino name.
[src:arduino/arduino] In August 2018, Arduino announced its new open source command line tool (arduino-cli), which can be used as a replacement of the IDE to program the boards from a shell.
[src:arduino/arduino] In February 2019, Arduino announced its IoT Cloud service as an extension of the Create online environment.
[src:arduino/arduino] As of February 2020, the Arduino community included about 30 million active users based on the IDE downloads.
[src:arduino/arduino] In October 2025 it was announced that Arduino has been acquired, for an as yet undisclosed amount, by the American semiconductor multinational Qualcomm.
[src:arduino/arduino] The hardware reference designs are distributed under a Creative Commons Attribution Share-Alike 2.5 license and are available on the Arduino website.
[src:arduino/arduino] Although the hardware and software designs are freely available under copyleft licenses, the developers have requested the name *Arduino* to be exclusive to the official product and not be used for derived works without permission.
[src:arduino/arduino] The official policy document on the use of the Arduino name emphasizes that the project is open to incorporating work by others into the official product.
[src:arduino/arduino] Several Arduino-compatible products commercially released have avoided the project name by using various names ending in *-duino*.
[src:arduino/arduino] Most Arduino boards consist of an Atmel 8-bit AVR microcontroller (ATmega8, ATmega168, ATmega328, ATmega1280, or ATmega2560) with varying amounts of flash memory, pins, and features.
[src:arduino/arduino] The 32-bit Arduino Due, based on the Atmel SAM3X8E was introduced in 2012.
[src:arduino/arduino] The boards use single or double-row pins or female headers that facilitate connections for programming and incorporation into other circuits.
[src:arduino/arduino] These may connect with add-on modules termed *shields*.
[src:arduino/arduino] Multiple and possibly stacked shields may be individually addressable via an I²C serial bus.
[src:arduino/arduino] Most boards include a 5 V linear regulator and a 16 MHz crystal oscillator or ceramic resonator.
[src:arduino/arduino] Some designs, such as the LilyPad, run at 8 MHz and dispense with the onboard voltage regulator due to specific form factor restrictions.
[src:arduino/arduino] Arduino microcontrollers are pre-programmed with a bootloader that simplifies the uploading of programs to the on-chip flash memory.
[src:arduino/arduino] The default bootloader of the Arduino Uno is the Optiboot bootloader.
[src:arduino/arduino] Boards are loaded with program code via a serial connection to another computer.
[src:arduino/arduino] Some serial Arduino boards contain a level shifter circuit to convert between RS-232 logic levels and transistor–transistor logic (TTL serial) level signals.
[src:arduino/arduino] Current Arduino boards are programmed via Universal Serial Bus (USB), implemented using USB-to-serial adapter chips such as the FTDI FT232.
[src:arduino/arduino] Some boards, such as later-model Uno boards, substitute the FTDI chip with a separate AVR chip containing USB-to-serial firmware, which is reprogrammable via its own ICSP header.
[src:arduino/arduino] Other variants, such as the Arduino Mini and the unofficial Boarduino, use a detachable USB-to-serial adapter board or cable, Bluetooth or other methods.
[src:arduino/arduino] When used with traditional microcontroller tools, instead of the Arduino IDE, standard AVR in-system programming (ISP) programming is used.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino board exposes most of the microcontroller's I/O pins for use by other circuits.
[src:arduino/arduino] The *Diecimila*, *Duemilanove*, and current *Uno* provide 14 digital I/O pins, six of which can produce pulse-width modulated(PWM) signals, and six analog inputs, which can also be used as six digital I/O pins.
[src:arduino/arduino] These pins are on the top of the board, via female 0.1-inch (2.54 mm) headers.
[src:arduino/arduino] Several plug-in application shields are also commercially available.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino Nano and Arduino-compatible Bare Bones Board and Boarduino boards may provide male header pins on the underside of the board that can plug into solderless breadboards.
[src:arduino/arduino] Many Arduino-compatible and Arduino-derived boards exist.
[src:arduino/arduino] Some are functionally equivalent to an Arduino and can be used interchangeably.
[src:arduino/arduino] Many enhance the basic Arduino by adding output drivers, often for use in school-level education, to simplify making buggies and small robots.
[src:arduino/arduino] Others are electrically equivalent, but change the form factor, sometimes retaining compatibility with shields, sometimes not.
[src:arduino/arduino] Some variants use different processors, of varying compatibility.
[src:arduino/arduino] In addition to hardware variations, open source libraries have been developed to support Arduino hardware in EDA tools.
[src:arduino/arduino] One such project provides KiCad schematic symbols and PCB footprints for Arduino modules, expansion boards, and connectors, making it easier for engineers to integrate Arduino into their designs.
[src:arduino/arduino] The original Arduino hardware was manufactured by the Italian company Smart Projects.
[src:arduino/arduino] Some Arduino-branded boards have been designed by the American companies SparkFun Electronics and Adafruit Industries.
[src:arduino/arduino] As of 2016, 17 versions of the Arduino hardware have been commercially produced.
[src:arduino/arduino] Arduino shields are add-on boards that stack onto Arduino mainboards to extend their functionality for specific tasks.
[src:arduino/arduino] Common uses include controlling DC motors for a robot, for 3D printer, adding a LCD display, enabling Ethernet connectivity, providing GPS/ GNSS navigation and converting pin headers into Grove connectors.
[src:arduino/arduino] Shields are typically designed and manufactured by third-party hardware companies, including SparkFun Electronics, Adafruit Industries, Seeed Studio, and Cytron Technologies, among others.
[src:arduino/arduino] Several shields can also be made do it yourself (DIY).
[src:arduino/arduino] A program for Arduino hardware may be written in any programming language with compilers that produce binary machine code for the target processor.
[src:arduino/arduino] Atmel provides a development environment for their 8-bit AVR and 32-bit ARM Cortex-M based microcontrollers: AVR Studio (older) and Atmel Studio (newer).
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino integrated development environment (IDE) is a cross-platform application (for Microsoft Windows, macOS, and Linux) that is based on *Processing IDE* which is written in Java.
[src:arduino/arduino] It uses the *Wiring* API as programming style and HAL.
[src:arduino/arduino] It includes a code editor with features such as text cutting and pasting, searching and replacing text, automatic indenting, brace matching, and syntax highlighting, and provides simple *one-click* mechanisms to compile and upload programs to an Arduino board.
[src:arduino/arduino] It also contains a message area, a text console, a toolbar with buttons for common functions and a hierarchy of operation menus.
[src:arduino/arduino] The source code for the IDE is released under the GNU General Public License, version 2.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino IDE supports the languages C and C++ using special rules of code structuring.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino IDE supplies a software library from the Wiring project, which provides many common input and output procedures.
[src:arduino/arduino] User-written code only requires two basic functions, for starting the sketch and the main program loop, that are compiled and linked with a program stub *main()* into an executable cyclic executive program with the GNU toolchain, also included with the IDE distribution.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino IDE employs the program *avrdude* to convert the executable code into a text file in hexadecimal encoding that is loaded into the Arduino board by a loader program in the board's firmware.
[src:arduino/arduino] An initial alpha preview of a new Arduino IDE was released on October 18, 2019, as Arduino Pro IDE.
[src:arduino/arduino] The beta preview was released on March 1, 2021, renamed IDE 2.0.
[src:arduino/arduino] On September 14, 2022, the Arduino IDE 2.0 was officially released as stable.
[src:arduino/arduino] The system still uses Arduino CLI (Command Line Interface), but improvements include a more professional development environment and autocompletion support.
[src:arduino/arduino] The application frontend is based on the Eclipse Theia Open Source IDE.
[src:arduino/arduino] One important feature Arduino IDE 2.0 provides is the debugging feature.
[src:arduino/arduino] It allows users to single-step, insert breakpoints or view memory.
[src:arduino/arduino] Debugging requires a target chip with debug port and a debug probe.
[src:arduino/arduino] The official Arduino Zero board can be debugged out of the box.
[src:arduino/arduino] Other official Arduino SAMD21 boards require a separate SEGGER J-Link or Atmel-ICE.
[src:arduino/arduino] For a 3rd party board, debugging in Arduino IDE 2.0 is also possible as long as such board supports GDB, OPENOCD and has a debug probe.
[src:arduino/arduino] Community has contributed debugging for ATMega328P based Arduino or CH32 RISC-V boards, etc.
[src:arduino/arduino] A *sketch* is a program written with the Arduino IDE.
[src:arduino/arduino] Sketches are saved on the development computer as text files with the file extension **.ino**.
[src:arduino/arduino] Arduino Software (IDE) pre-1.0 saved sketches with the extension **.pde**.
[src:arduino/arduino] Most Arduino boards contain a light-emitting diode (LED) and a current-limiting resistor connected between pin 13 and ground, which is a convenient feature for many tests and program functions.
[src:arduino/arduino] A typical program used by beginners, akin to Hello, World!, is "blink", which repeatedly blinks the on-board LED integrated into the Arduino board.
[src:arduino/arduino] This program uses the functions `pinMode()`, `digitalWrite()`, and `delay()`, which are provided by the internal libraries included in the IDE environment.
[src:arduino/arduino] This program is usually loaded into a new Arduino board by the manufacturer.
[src:arduino/arduino] The open-source nature of the Arduino project has facilitated the publication of many free software libraries that other developers use to augment their projects.
[src:arduino/arduino] There is a Xinu OS port for the ATmega328P (Arduino Uno and others with the same chip), which includes most of the basic features.
[src:arduino/arduino] The source code of this version is freely available.
[src:arduino/arduino] There is also a threading tool, named Protothreads.
[src:arduino/arduino] Protothreads are described as "extremely lightweight stackless threads designed for severely memory constrained systems, such as small embedded systems or wireless sensor network nodes.
[src:arduino/arduino] There is a port of FreeRTOS for the Arduino.
[src:arduino/arduino] This is available from the Arduino Library Manager.
[src:arduino/arduino] It is compatible with a number of boards, including the Uno.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino project received an honorary mention in the Digital Communities category at the 2006 Prix Ars Electronica.
[src:arduino/arduino] The Arduino Engineering Kit won the Bett Award for "Higher Education or Further Education Digital Services" in 2020.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The **Atmel AVR instruction set** is the machine language for the Atmel AVR, a modified Harvard architecture 8-bit RISC single chip microcontroller which was developed by Atmel in 1996.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Atmel was acquired by Microchip Technology in 2016.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The AVR was one of the first microcontroller families to use on-chip flash memory for program storage.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] There are 32 general-purpose 8-bit registers, R0–R31.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] All arithmetic and logic operations operate on those registers; only load and store instructions access RAM.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] A limited number of instructions operate on 16-bit register pairs.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The lower-numbered register of the pair holds the least significant bits and must be even-numbered.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The last three register pairs are used as pointer registers for memory addressing.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Postincrement and predecrement addressing modes are supported on all three.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Y and Z also support a six-bit positive displacement.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Instructions which allow an immediate value are limited to registers R16–R31 (8-bit operations) or to register pairs R25:R24–R31:R30 (16-bit operations ADIW and SBIW).
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Some variants of the MUL operation are limited to eight registers, R16 through R23.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Set when an arithmetic result is zero, and cleared when it is non-zero.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Set to a copy of the most significant bit of an arithmetic result.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Set in case of two's complement overflow.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Unique to AVR, this is always N⊕V, and shows the true sign of a comparison.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] This is an internal carry from additions and is used to support BCD arithmetic.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Special bit load and bit store instructions use this bit.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The first 64 I/O registers are accessible through both the I/O and the data address space.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] They have therefore two different addresses.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] These are usually written as "0x00 (0x20)" through "0x3F (0x5F)", where the first item is the I/O address and the second, in parentheses, the data address.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The special-purpose CPU registers, with the exception of PC, can be accessed as I/O registers.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Some registers (RAMPX, RAMPY) may not be present on machines with less than 64 KiB of addressable memory.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] In parts lacking extended I/O the RAM would start at 0x0060.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Arithmetic operations work on registers R0–R31 but not directly on RAM and take one clock cycle, except for multiplication and word-wide addition (ADIW and SBIW) which take two cycles.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] RAM and I/O space can be accessed only by copying to or from registers.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Indirect access (including optional postincrement, predecrement or constant displacement) is possible through registers X, Y, and Z.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] All accesses to RAM takes two clock cycles.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Moving between registers and I/O is one cycle.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Moving eight or sixteen bit data between registers or constant to register is also one cycle.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Reading program memory (LPM) takes three cycles.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Instructions are one 16-bit long word, save for those including a 16-bit or 22-bit address, which take two words.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] There are two types of conditional branches: jumps to address and skips.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Conditional branches (BRxx) can test an ALU flag and jump to specified address.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Skips (SBxx) test an arbitrary bit in a register or I/O and skip the next instruction if the test was true.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Not all instructions are implemented in all Atmel AVR controllers.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] This is the case of the instructions performing multiplications, extended loads/jumps/calls, long jumps, and power control.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] While higher-end processors tend to have both more capable cores and more memory, the presence of one does not guarantee the presence of the other.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] "Classic plus" adds the `MOVW` instruction for moving register pairs, and the more general form of the LPM instruction (`LPM Rd,Z` and `LPM Rd,Z+`) which permit an arbitrary destination register and auto-increment of the Z pointer.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] "Enhanced" cores add the multiply instructions.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Later XMEGA cores (specifically, the B, C, and AU models such as the ATxmega16A4U, but *not* the earlier A, D and E models such as the ATxmega16D4) add four atomic read-modify-write instructions: exchange (`XCH`), load-and-set, load-and-clear, and load-and-toggle.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] These help coordinate with direct memory access peripherals, notably a USB controller.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Less capable than the "classic" CPU cores are two subsets: the "AVR1" core, and the "AVR tiny".
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Confusingly, "ATtiny" branded processors have a variety of cores, including AVR1 (ATtiny11, ATtiny28), classic (ATtiny22, ATtiny26), classic+ (ATtiny24) and AVRtiny (ATtiny20, ATtiny40).
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The AVR1 subset was not popular and no new models have been introduced since 2000.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] It omits all RAM except for the 32 registers mapped at address 0–31 and the I/O ports at addresses 32–95.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The stack is replaced by a 3-level hardware stack, and the `PUSH` and `POP` instructions are deleted.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] All 16-bit operations are deleted, as are `IJMP`, `ICALL`, and all load and store addressing modes except indirect via Z.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] A second, more successful attempt to subset the AVR instruction set is the "AVR tiny" core.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The most significant change is that the AVRtiny core omits registers R0–R15.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The registers are also not memory-mapped, with I/O ports from 0–63 and general-purpose RAM beginning at address 64.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The 16-bit arithmetic operations (`ADIW`, `SBIW`) are omitted, as are the load/store with displacement addressing modes (`Y+d`, `Z+d`), but the predecrement and postincrement addressing modes are retained.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The `LPM` instruction is omitted; instead program ROM is mapped to the data address space and may be accessed with normal load instructions.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The smallest cores have ≤256 bytes of data address space (meaning ≤128 bytes of RAM after I/O ports and other reserved addresses are removed) and ≤8192 bytes (8 KiB) of program ROM.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] These have only an 8-bit stack pointer (in SPL), and only support the 12-bit relative jump/call instructions `RJMP`/`RCALL`.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Models with >8 KiB of ROM add the 2-word (22-bit) `JUMP` and `CALL` instructions.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Models with >64 KiB of ROM add the `ELPM` instruction and corresponding RAMPZ register.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] `LPM` instructions zero-extend the ROM address in Z; `ELPM` instructions prepend the RAMPZ register for high bits.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] This is not the same thing as the more general `LPM` instruction; there exist "classic" models with only the zero-operand form of `ELPM` (ATmega103 and at43usb320).
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] When auto-increment is available (most models), it updates the entire 24-bit address including RAMPZ.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] (Rare) models with >128 KiB of ROM have a 3-byte program counter.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Subroutine calls and returns use an additional byte of stack space, there is a new EIND register to provide additional high bits for indirect jumps and calls, and there are new extended instructions `EIJMP` and `EICALL` which use EIND:Z as the destination address.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] (Rare) models with >64 KiB of RAM address space extend the 16-bit RAM addressing limits with RAMPX, RAMPY, RAMPZ and RAMPD registers.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] These provide additional high bits for addressing modes which use the X, Y, or Z register pairs, respectively, or the direct addressing instructions `LDS`/`STS`.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Unlike ROM access, there are no distinct "extended" instructions; instead the RAMP registers are used unconditionally.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] Architectures other than AVR1 are named according to avr-libc conventions.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The Atmel AVR uses many split fields, where bits are not contiguous in the instruction word.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The most commonly encountered is the 5-bit source register field in bits 9 and 3–0.
[src:arduino/atmel-avr-instruction-set] The most extreme example is the load/store with offset instructions, which break a 6-bit offset into three pieces.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] AVR microcontrollers are used numerously as embedded systems.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] They are especially common in hobbyist and educational embedded applications, popularized by their inclusion in many of the Arduino line of open hardware development boards.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR 8-bit microcontroller architecture was introduced in 1997.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] By 2003, Atmel had shipped 500 million AVR flash microcontrollers.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR architecture was conceived by two students at the Norwegian Institute of Technology (NTH), Alf-Egil Bogen and Vegard Wollan.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Atmel says that the name AVR is not an acronym and does not stand for anything in particular.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The creators of the AVR give no definitive answer as to what the term "AVR" stands for.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] However, it is commonly accepted that AVR stands for **A**lf and **V**egard's **R**ISC processor.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Note that the use of "AVR" in this article generally refers to the 8-bit RISC line of Atmel AVR microcontrollers.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The original AVR MCU was developed at a local ASIC design company in Trondheim, Norway, called Nordic VLSI at the time, now Nordic Semiconductor, where Bogen and Wollan were working as students.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It was known as a μRISC (Micro RISC) and was available as silicon IP/building block from Nordic VLSI.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] When the technology was sold to Atmel from Nordic VLSI, the internal architecture was further developed by Bogen and Wollan at Atmel Norway, a subsidiary of Atmel.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The designers worked closely with compiler writers at IAR Systems to ensure that the AVR instruction set provided efficient compilation of high-level languages.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Among the first of the AVR line was the AT90S8515, which in a 40-pin DIP package has the same pinout as an 8051 microcontroller, including the external multiplexed address and data bus.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The polarity of the RESET line was opposite (8051's having an active-high RESET, while the AVR has an active-low RESET), but other than that the pinout was identical.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Arduino platform, developed for simple electronics projects, was released in 2005 and featured ATmega8 AVR microcontrollers.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR is a modified Harvard architecture machine, where program and data are stored in separate physical memory systems that appear in different address spaces, but having the ability to read data items from program memory using special instructions.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The ATtiny series features small package microcontrollers with a limited peripheral set available.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The ATmega series features microcontrollers that provide an extended instruction set (multiply instructions and instructions for handling larger program memories), an extensive peripheral set, a solid amount of program memory, as well as a wide range of pins available.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The parts numbers is formatted as AVR*ff*D*xpp*, where *ff* is flash size, *x* is family, and *pp* is number of pins.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Example: AVR128DA64 – 64-pin DA-series with 128k flash.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVRs have 32 single-byte registers and are classified as 8-bit RISC devices.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Flash, EEPROM, and SRAM are all integrated onto a single chip, removing the need for external memory in most applications.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Some devices have a parallel external bus option to allow adding additional data memory or memory-mapped devices.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Almost all devices (except the smallest TinyAVR chips) have serial interfaces, which can be used to connect larger serial EEPROMs or flash chips.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Program instructions are stored in non-volatile flash memory.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Although the MCUs are 8-bit, each instruction takes one or two 16-bit words.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The size of the program memory is usually indicated in the naming of the device itself (e.g., the ATmega64x line has 64 KB of flash, while the ATmega32x line has 32 KB).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] There is no provision for off-chip program memory; all code executed by the AVR core must reside in the on-chip flash.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] However, this limitation does not apply to the AT94 FPSLIC AVR/FPGA chips.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The data address space consists of the register file, I/O registers, and SRAM.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Some small models also map the program ROM into the data address space, but larger models do not.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In the tinyAVR and megaAVR variants of the AVR architecture, the working registers are mapped in as the first 32 data memory addresses (000016–001F16), followed by 64 I/O registers (002016–005F16).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In devices with many peripherals, these registers are followed by 160 “extended I/O” registers, only accessible as memory-mapped I/O (006016–00FF16).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Actual SRAM starts after these register sections, at address 006016 or, in devices with "extended I/O", at 010016.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Even though there are separate addressing schemes and optimized opcodes for accessing the register file and the first 64 I/O registers, all can also be addressed and manipulated as if they were in SRAM.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The very smallest of the tinyAVR variants use a reduced architecture with only 16 registers (r0 through r15 are omitted) which are not addressable as memory locations.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] I/O memory begins at address 000016, followed by SRAM.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In addition, these devices have slight deviations from the standard AVR instruction set.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Most notably, the direct load/store instructions (LDS/STS) have been reduced from 2 words (32 bits) to 1 word (16 bits), limiting the total direct addressable memory (the sum of both I/O and SRAM) to 128 bytes.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Conversely, the indirect load instruction's (LD) 16-bit address space is expanded to also include non-volatile memory such as Flash and configuration bits; therefore, the Load Program Memory (LPM) instruction is unnecessary and omitted.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In the XMEGA variant, the working register file is not mapped into the data address space; as such, it is not possible to treat any of the XMEGA's working registers as though they were SRAM.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Instead, the I/O registers are mapped into the data address space starting at the very beginning of the address space.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Additionally, the amount of data address space dedicated to I/O registers has grown substantially to 4096 bytes (000016–0FFF16).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] As with previous generations, however, the fast I/O manipulation instructions can only reach the first 64 I/O register locations (the first 32 locations for bitwise instructions).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Following the I/O registers, the XMEGA series sets aside a 4096 byte range of the data address space, which can be used optionally for mapping the internal EEPROM to the data address space (100016–1FFF16).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The actual SRAM is located after these ranges, starting at 200016.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Each GPIO port on a tiny or mega AVR drives up to eight pins and is controlled by three 8-bit registers: DDR*x*, PORT*x* and PIN*x*, where *x* is the port identifier.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Newer ATtiny AVRs, like ATtiny817 and its siblings, have their port control registers somewhat differently defined. xmegaAVR have additional registers for push/pull, totem-pole and pullup configurations.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Almost all AVR microcontrollers have internal EEPROM for semi-permanent data storage.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Like flash memory, EEPROM can maintain its contents when electrical power is removed.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In most variants of the AVR architecture, this internal EEPROM memory is not mapped into the MCU's addressable memory space.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It can only be accessed the same way an external peripheral device is, using special pointer registers and read/write instructions, which makes EEPROM access much slower than other internal RAM.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] However, some devices in the SecureAVR (AT90SC) family use a special EEPROM mapping to the data or program memory, depending on the configuration.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The XMEGA family also allows the EEPROM to be mapped into the data address space.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Since the number of writes to EEPROM is limited – Atmel specifies 100,000 write cycles in their datasheets – a well designed EEPROM write routine should compare the contents of an EEPROM address with desired contents and only perform an actual write if the contents need to be changed.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Atmel's AVRs have a two-stage, single-level pipeline design, meaning that the next machine instruction is fetched as the current one is executing.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Most instructions take just one or two clock cycles, making AVRs relatively fast among eight-bit microcontrollers.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR processors were designed with the efficient execution of compiled C code in mind and have several built-in pointers for the task.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR instruction set is more orthogonal than those of most eight-bit microcontrollers, in particular the 8051 clones and PIC microcontrollers with which AVR has competed.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Some chip-specific differences affect code generation.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Code pointers (including return addresses on the stack) are two bytes long on chips with up to 128 KB of flash memory, but three bytes long on larger chips; not all chips have hardware multipliers; chips with over 8 KB of flash have branch and call instructions with longer ranges; and so forth.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The mostly regular instruction set makes C (and even Ada) compilers fairly straightforward and efficient.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] GCC has included AVR support for quite some time, and that support is widely used.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In fact, Atmel solicited input from major developers of compilers for small microcontrollers, to determine the instruction set features that were most useful in a compiler for high-level languages.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR line can normally support clock speeds from 0 to 20 MHz, with some devices reaching 32 MHz.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Lower-powered operation usually requires a reduced clock speed.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] All recent (Tiny, Mega, and Xmega, but not 90S) AVRs feature an on-chip oscillator, removing the need for external clocks or resonator circuitry.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Some AVRs also have a system clock prescaler that can divide down the system clock by up to 1024.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] This prescaler can be reconfigured by software during run-time, allowing the clock speed to be optimized.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Since all operations (excluding multiplication and 16-bit add/subtract) on registers R0–R31 are single-cycle, the AVR can achieve up to 1 MIPS per MHz, i.e. an 8 MHz processor can achieve up to 8 MIPS.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Loads and stores to/from memory take two cycles, branching takes two cycles.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Branches in the latest "3-byte PC" parts such as ATmega2560 are one cycle slower than on previous devices.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] AVRs have a large following due to the free and inexpensive development tools available, including reasonably priced development boards and free development software.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVRs are sold under various names that share the same basic core, but with different peripheral and memory combinations.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Compatibility between chips in each family is fairly good, although I/O controller features may vary.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Atmel AVR GNU C/C++ cross compiler, "avr-gcc" and "avr-g++", is used in both WinAVR and Atmel Studio.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Arduino team borrowed from WinAVR for the Windows version of the Arduino software.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] See external links for sites relating to AVR development.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] There are many means to load program code into an AVR chip.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The methods to program AVR chips varies from AVR family to family.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Most of the methods described below use the RESET line to enter programming mode.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In order to avoid the chip accidentally entering such mode, it is advised to connect a pull-up resistor between the RESET pin and the positive power supply.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The in-system programming (ISP) programming method is functionally performed through SPI, plus some twiddling of the Reset line.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] As long as the SPI pins of the AVR are not connected to anything disruptive, the AVR chip can stay soldered on a PCB while reprogramming.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] All that is needed is a 6-pin connector and programming adapter.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] This is the most common way to develop with an AVR.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Atmel-ICE device or AVRISP mkII (Legacy device) connects to a computer's USB port and performs in-system programming using Atmel's software.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] AVRDUDE (AVR Downloader/UploaDEr) runs on Linux, FreeBSD, Windows, and Mac OS X, and supports a variety of in-system programming hardware, including Atmel AVRISP mkII, Atmel JTAG ICE, older Atmel serial-port based programmers, and various third-party and "do-it-yourself" programmers.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Program and Debug Interface (PDI) is an Atmel proprietary interface for external programming and on-chip debugging of XMEGA devices.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The PDI supports high-speed programming of all non-volatile memory (NVM) spaces; flash, EEPROM, fuses, lock-bits and the User Signature Row.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] This is done by accessing the XMEGA NVM controller through the PDI interface, and executing NVM controller commands.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The PDI is a 2-pin interface using the Reset pin for clock input (PDI_CLK) and a dedicated data pin (PDI_DATA) for input and output.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Unified Program and Debug Interface (UPDI) is a one-wire interface for external programming and on-chip debugging of newer ATtiny and ATmega devices.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] UPDI chips can be programmed by an Atmel-ICE, a PICkit 4, an Arduino (flashed with jtag2updi), or though a UART (with a 1 kΩ resistor between the TX and RX pins) controlled by Microchip's Python utility pymcuprog.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] High-voltage serial programming (HVSP) is mostly the backup mode on smaller AVRs.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] An 8-pin AVR package does not leave many unique signal combinations to place the AVR into a programming mode.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] A 12-volt signal, however, is something the AVR should only see during programming and never during normal operation.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The high voltage mode can also be used in some devices where the reset pin was disabled by fuses.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] High-voltage parallel programming (HVPP) is considered the "final resort" and may be the only way to correct bad fuse settings on an AVR chip.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Most AVR models can reserve a bootloader region, 256 bytes to 4 KB, where re-programming code can reside.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] At reset, the bootloader runs first and does some user-programmed determination whether to re-program or to jump to the main application.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The code can re-program through any interface available, or it could read an encrypted binary through an Ethernet adapter like PXE.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Atmel has application notes and code pertaining to many bus interfaces.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AT90SC series of AVRs are available with a factory mask-ROM for program memory, instead of flash.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Because of the large up-front cost and minimum order quantity, a mask-ROM is only cost-effective for high-production runs.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] aWire is a new one-wire debug interface available on the new UC3L AVR32 devices.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR offers several options for debugging, mostly involving on-chip debugging while the chip is in the target system.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] debugWIRE is Atmel's solution for providing on-chip debug capabilities via a single microcontroller pin.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It is useful for lower pin-count parts which cannot provide the four "spare" pins needed for JTAG.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAGICE mkII, mkIII and the AVR Dragon support debugWIRE. debugWIRE was developed after the original JTAGICE release, and now clones support it.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Joint Test Action Group (JTAG) feature provides access to on-chip debugging functionality while the chip is running in the target system.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] JTAG allows accessing internal memory and registers, setting breakpoints on code, and single-stepping execution to observe system behaviour.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAGICE 3 is a midrange debugger in the JTAGICE family (JTAGICE mkIII).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It supports JTAG, aWire, SPI, and PDI interfaces.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAGICE mkII replaces the JTAGICE and is similarly priced.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAGICE mkII interfaces to the PC via USB, and supports both JTAG and the newer debugWIRE interface.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Numerous third-party clones of the Atmel JTAGICE mkII device started shipping after Atmel released the communication protocol.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR Dragon is a low-cost (approximately $50) substitute for the JTAGICE mkII for certain target parts.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR Dragon provides in-system serial programming, high-voltage serial programming and parallel programming, as well as JTAG or debugWIRE emulation for parts with 32 KB of program memory or less.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] ATMEL changed the debugging feature of AVR Dragon with the latest firmware of AVR Studio 4 – AVR Studio 5 and now it supports devices over 32 KB of program memory.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAGICE adapter interfaces to the PC via a standard serial port.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Although the JTAGICE adapter has been declared "end-of-life" by Atmel, it is still supported in AVR Studio and other tools.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] JTAG can also be used to perform a boundary scan test, which tests the electrical connections between AVRs and other boundary scan capable chips in a system.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Boundary scan is well-suited for a production line, while the hobbyist is probably better off testing with a multimeter or oscilloscope.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The STK600 starter kit and development system is an update to the STK500.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The STK600 uses a base board, a signal routing board, and a target board.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The base board is similar to the STK500, in that it provides a power supply, clock, in-system programming, an RS-232 port and a CAN (Controller Area Network, an automotive standard) port via DE9 connectors, and stake pins for all of the GPIO signals from the target device.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The target boards have ZIF sockets for DIP, SOIC, QFN, or QFP packages, depending on the board.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The signal routing board sits between the base board and the target board, and routes the signals to the proper pin on the device board.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] There are many different signal routing boards that could be used with a single target board, depending on what device is in the ZIF socket.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The STK600 allows in-system programming from the PC via USB, leaving the RS-232 port available for the target microcontroller.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] A 4 pin header on the STK600 labeled 'RS-232 spare' can connect any TTL level USART port on the chip to an onboard MAX232 chip to translate the signals to RS-232 levels.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The RS-232 signals are connected to the RX, TX, CTS, and RTS pins on the DB-9 connector.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The STK500 starter kit and development system features ISP and high voltage programming (HVP) for all AVR devices, either directly or through extension boards.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The board is fitted with DIP sockets for all AVRs available in DIP packages.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The STK200 starter kit and development system has a DIP socket that can host an AVR chip in a 40, 20, or 8-pin package.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The board has a 4 MHz clock source, 8 light-emitting diode (LED)s, 8 input buttons, an RS-232 port, a socket for a 32 KB SRAM and numerous general I/O.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The chip can be programmed with a dongle connected to the parallel port.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Atmel ICE is the currently supported inexpensive tool to program and debug all AVR devices (unlike the AVRISP/AVRISP mkII, Dragon, etc. discussed below).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It connects to and receives power from a PC via USB, and supports JTAG, PDI, aWire, debugWIRE, SPI, SWD, TPI, and UPDI (the Microchip Unified Program and Debug Interface) interfaces.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The ICE is supported by the Microchip Studio IDE, as well as a command line interface (atprogram).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Atmel-ICE supports a limited implementation of the Data Gateway Interface (DGI) when debugging and programming features are not in use.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Data Gateway Interface is an interface for streaming data from a target device to the connected computer.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] This is meant as a useful adjunct to the unit to allow for demonstration of application features and as an aid in application level debugging.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVRISP and AVRISP mkII are inexpensive tools allowing all AVRs to be programmed via ICSP.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVRISP connects to a PC via a serial port and draws power from the target system.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVRISP allows using either of the "standard" ICSP pinouts, either the 10-pin or 6-pin connector.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVRISP mkII connects to a PC via USB and draws power from USB.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] LEDs visible through the translucent case indicate the state of target power.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] As the AVRISP mkII lacks driver/buffer ICs, it can have trouble programming target boards with multiple loads on its SPI lines.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In such occurrences, a programmer capable of sourcing greater current is required.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Alternatively, the AVRISP mkII can still be used if low-value (~150 ohm) load-limiting resistors can be placed on the SPI lines before each peripheral device.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Both the AVRISP and the AVRISP mkII are now discontinued, with product pages removed from the Microchip website.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] As of July 2019 the AVRISP mkII is still in stock at a number of distributors.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] There are also a number of 3rd party clones available.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Atmel Dragon is an inexpensive tool which connects to a PC via USB.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Dragon can program all AVRs via JTAG, HVP, PDI, or ICSP.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Dragon also allows debugging of all AVRs via JTAG, PDI, or debugWire; a previous limitation to devices with 32 KB or less program memory has been removed in AVR Studio 4.18.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Dragon has a small prototype area which can accommodate an 8, 28, or 40-pin AVR, including connections to power and programming pins.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] There is no area for any additional circuitry, although this can be provided by a third-party product called the "Dragon Rider".
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAG In Circuit Emulator (JTAGICE) debugging tool supports on-chip debugging (OCD) of AVRs with a JTAG interface.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The original JTAGICE (sometimes retroactively referred to as JTAGICE mkI) uses an RS-232 interface to a PC and can only program AVRs with a JTAG interface.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAGICE mkI is no longer in production, however it has been replaced by the JTAGICE mkII.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAGICE mkII debugging tool supports on-chip debugging (OCD) of AVRs with SPI, JTAG, PDI, and debugWIRE interfaces.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The debugWire interface enables debugging using only one pin (the Reset pin), allowing debugging of applications running on low pin-count microcontrollers.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAGICE mkII connects using USB, but there is an alternate connection via a serial port, which requires using a separate power supply.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In addition to JTAG, the mkII supports ISP programming (using 6-pin or 10-pin adapters).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Both the USB and serial links use a variant of the STK500 protocol.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The JTAGICE3 updates the mkII with more advanced debugging capabilities and faster programming.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It connects via USB and supports the JTAG, aWire, SPI, and PDI interfaces.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The kit includes several adapters for use with most interface pinouts.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR ONE! is a professional development tool for all Atmel 8-bit and 32-bit AVR devices with On-Chip Debug capability.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It supports SPI, JTAG, PDI, and aWire programming modes and debugging using debugWIRE, JTAG, PDI, and aWire interfaces.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The very popular AVR Butterfly demonstration board is a self-contained, battery-powered computer running the Atmel AVR ATmega169V microcontroller.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It was built to show off the AVR family, especially a then new built-in LCD interface.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The board includes the LCD screen, joystick, speaker, serial port, real time clock (RTC), flash memory chip, and both temperature and voltage sensors.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Earlier versions of the AVR Butterfly also contained a CdS photoresistor; it is not present on Butterfly boards produced after June 2006 to allow RoHS compliance.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The small board has a shirt pin on its back so it can be worn as a name badge.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR Butterfly comes preloaded with software to demonstrate the capabilities of the microcontroller.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Factory firmware can scroll your name, display the sensor readings, and show the time.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR Butterfly also has a piezoelectric transducer that can be used to reproduce sounds and music.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR Butterfly demonstrates LCD driving by running a 14-segment, six alpha-numeric character display.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] However, the LCD interface consumes many of the I/O pins.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Butterfly's ATmega169 CPU is capable of speeds up to 8 MHz, but it is factory set by software to 2 MHz to preserve the button battery life.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] A pre-installed bootloader program allows the board to be re-programmed via a standard RS-232 serial plug with new programs that users can write with the free Atmel IDE tools.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] This small board, about half the size of a business card, is priced at slightly more than an AVR Butterfly.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It includes an AT90USB1287 with USB On-The-Go (OTG) support, 16 MB of DataFlash, LEDs, a small joystick, and a temperature sensor.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The board includes software, which lets it act as a USB mass storage device (its documentation is shipped on the DataFlash), a USB joystick, and more.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] To support the USB host capability, it must be operated from a battery, but when running as a USB peripheral, it only needs the power provided over USB.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Only the JTAG port uses conventional 2.54 mm pinout.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] All the other AVR I/O ports require more compact 1.27 mm headers.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The AVR Dragon can both program and debug since the 32 KB limitation was removed in AVR Studio 4.18, and the JTAGICE mkII is capable of both programming and debugging the processor.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The processor can also be programmed through USB from a Windows or Linux host, using the USB "Device Firmware Update" protocols.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Atmel ships proprietary (source code included but distribution restricted) example programs and a USB protocol stack with the device.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] LUFA is a third-party free software (MIT license) USB protocol stack for the USBKey and other 8-bit USB AVRs.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The RAVEN kit supports wireless development using Atmel's IEEE 802.15.4 chipsets, for Zigbee and other wireless stacks.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] It resembles a pair of wireless more-powerful Butterfly cards, plus a wireless USBKey; and costing about that much (under $US100).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] All these boards support JTAG-based development.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The kit includes two AVR Raven boards, each with a 2.4 GHz transceiver supporting IEEE 802.15.4 (and a freely licensed Zigbee stack).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The radios are driven with ATmega1284p processors, which are supported by a custom segmented LCD driven by an ATmega3290p processor.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Raven peripherals resemble the Butterfly: piezo speaker, DataFlash (bigger), external EEPROM, sensors, 32 kHz crystal for RTC, and so on.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] These are intended for use in developing remote sensor nodes, to control relays, or whatever is needed.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The USB stick uses an AT90USB1287 for connections to a USB host and to the 2.4 GHz wireless links.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] These are intended to monitor and control the remote nodes, relying on host power rather than local batteries.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] A wide variety of third-party programming and debugging tools are available for the AVR.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] These devices use various interfaces, including RS-232, PC parallel port, and USB.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] AVRs have been used in various automotive applications such as security, safety, powertrain and entertainment systems.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Atmel has recently launched a new publication "Atmel Automotive Compilation" to help developers with automotive applications.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Some current usages are in BMW, Daimler-Chrysler and TRW.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The Arduino physical computing platform is based on an ATmega328 microcontroller (ATmega168 or ATmega8 in board versions older than the Diecimila).
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The ATmega1280 and ATmega2560, with more pinout and memory capabilities, have also been employed to develop the Arduino Mega platform.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Arduino boards can be used with its language and IDE, or with more conventional programming environments (C, assembler, etc.) as just standardized and widely available AVR platforms.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] USB-based AVRs have been used in the Microsoft Xbox hand controllers.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] The link between the controllers and Xbox is USB.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Numerous companies produce AVR-based microcontroller boards intended for use by hobbyists, robot builders, experimenters and small system developers including: Cubloc, gnusb, BasicX, Oak Micros, ZX Microcontrollers, and myAVR.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] There is also a large community of Arduino-compatible boards supporting similar users.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Schneider Electric used to produce the M3000 Motor and Motion Control Chip, incorporating an Atmel AVR Core and an advanced motion controller for use in a variety of motion applications but this has been discontinued.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] With the growing popularity of FPGAs among the open source community, people have started developing open source processors compatible with the AVR instruction set.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] In addition to the chips manufactured by Atmel, clones are available from LogicGreen Technologies.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] These parts are not exact clones – they have a few features not found in the chips they are "clones" of, and higher maximum clock speeds, but use SWD (Serial Wire Debug, a variant of JTAG from ARM) instead of ISP for programming, so different programming tools must be used.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] Microcontrollers using the ATmega architecture are being manufactured by NIIET in Voronezh, Russia, as part of the 1887 series of integrated circuits.
[src:arduino/avr-microcontrollers] This includes an ATmega128 under the designation 1887VE7T (Russian: *1887ВЕ7Т*).
